This also same it will start the accounts service or selected service as a spring boot application


There are 3 ways to generate a Docker Image
01- Dockerfile -> accounts
02- Buildpacks -> loans
03- Google jib -> cards

01- Dockerfile -> accounts:

FROM openjdk:17 -> Starts a base image containing the Java runtime
COPY target/accounts.jar accounts.jar -> Add's the application jar's to the image
ENTRYPOINT ["java","-jar","accounts.jar"] -> To execute the application or the one who tries to create a docker container with our docker image , they should follows these entrypoints

These commands helps to and convert a docker file into docker image

How to create a docker image with those :
docker build . -t dockerhubname/servicename:docker version

dockerhubname -> this is the hub where all the docker images are stored
servicename -> which service we are creating by
dockerversion -> any version

docker images - TO get list of images
docker inspect image imageid

docker run -p 8080:8080 name/servicename:version -> we can create docker container with image

docker run -d -p 8080:8080 name/servicename:version , it is to run the docker image in a detached mode, we cannot see any logs there

docker ps -> it is used to see the containers currently running

docker ps -a -> get all the containers which are stopped

Only 4 commands to convert any service into spring boot application using docker container
1.mvn clean install - 							we should run from the location where pom.xml is present to generate a JAR file inside Target folder
2.FROM, COPY, ENTRYPOINT  - 						These commands helps to and convert a docker file into docker image
3.docker build . -t dockerhubname/servicename:docker version - 		Will generate a docker image
4. docker run -p 8080:8080 name/servicename:version - 			We can create docker container with image

These Commands are very huge to generate a docker image and to build a container from it, So going forware we will use BuildPacks or Google Jibs to generate Images and generate Containers

How to Generate Docker Images using BuildPacks:

First add the 
<image>
	<name>somename/${project.artifactid}:s4</name>
</image>

mvn spring-boot:build-image - from the location where the pom.xml no need of docker file here , it will directly create the docker image.

docker run -p 8090:8090 somename/ourservicename:s4 , Starts the docker container based on the docker image details

How to Generate Docker Images using Google jibs: This is only used for Java Applications , but BuildPacks used for python, ruby, node.js

First add necessary tags

2.mvn complie jib:dockerBuild -> To generate a docker image 
3.docker run -p 9000:9000 somename/cards:s4 -> This will start the docker container on docker image and port mapping is provided

Even without docker app installed we can generate images with the help of google jibs with some amazon credentials etc which is now not needed to know.
This approach used in CI/CD Pipeline.

Google libs are used widely and BuildPacks have some issues to use.

